{
  "texts": [
    "The safety concern is not that users might mistake AI for humans per se, but rather that models overstate their expertise and capabilities.",
    "When models claim false professional credentials, users calibrate trust based on these overstated expertise claims, potentially treating AI-generated medical or financial guidance as equivalent to licensed professional advice [27].",
    "Cognitive science research on anthropomorphism in conversational AI suggests users may be particularly prone to such miscalibration, as language use triggers agency attribution that increases trust even when users are aware errors can occur [31].",
    "Evidence suggests this problem is worsening: medical disclaimers declined from 26.3% in 2022 to under 1% in 2025 despite capability improvements [36].This creates a concrete professional responsibility problem.",
    "Human professionals cannot ethically maintain false credentials without possessing training and licensure."
  ]
}